{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:40:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.12,0.07,0,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9778"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5189"},{"type":"tags","id":"7014"},{"type":"tags","id":"10150"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23178"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMelatonin is involved in regulating circadian rhythms and sleep-wake cycles. Its production follows a distinct pattern on a daily basis with levels rising at night and falling during daylight hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary site of melatonin synthesis and secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pineal gland","Hypothalamus","Pituitary gland","Retina","Suprachiasmatic nucleus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epineal gland\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary site of melatonin synthesis and secretion in the body. It receives input from the suprachiasmatic nucleus in the hypothylamus via a multisynaptic pathway to coordinate melatonin release with the light-dark cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E contains the suprachiasmatic nucleus which regulates melatonin production, it does not synthesise melatonin itself\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E secretes many hormones, but not melatonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eretina\u003C/strong\u003E contains photoreceptors that detect light and influence melatonin production but produces only small amounts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuprachiasmatic nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E acts as the body\u0027s master clock but does not produce melatonin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pineal gland synthesises melatonin from serotonin through enzymatic conversion. Production increases in darkness and decreases with light exposure, helping to regulate the sleep-wake cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melatonin is synthesised and secreted by the pineal gland in response to darkness.","Melatonin production is suppressed by light via signals from the suprachiasmatic nucleus.","The pineal gland converts serotonin to melatonin through a two-step enzymatic process."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Amar AP, Weiss MH. Pituitary anatomy and physiology. Neurosurg Clin N Am. 2003;14(1):11-v. doi:10.1016/s1042-3680(02)00017-7","Kennaway DJ. What do we really know about the safety and efficacy of melatonin for sleep disorders?. Curr Med Res Opin. 2022;38(2):211-227. doi:10.1080/03007995.2021.2000714"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T21:18:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:18:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9778"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"}